I think teen girls go through that ‚ÄúI‚Äôm not like other girls‚Äù phase in a dawning realization of internalized, cultural misogyny. I transferred into JMU from a different school. I'm really glad I made that choice. In my opinion, the experience you have at college is just as, if not more, important as the school you choose to go to. If you wind up at a prestigious college that you're completely miserable at, you're probably not going to do very well in your classes. You probably won't be inclined to network or become involved in things outside of the classroom if you hate the school, and both of those things can be very important. I think it's a very smart choice to choose the place where you're better set up for success.

Numbing is a bit different. I think that‚Äôs primarily related to decreased blood flow that occurs when you‚Äôre cold, leading to a reduction in the sensory signals being transmitted to your brain. Habituation is a process of how your body handles the signals your sensory organs pick up. A good example of this is something called the cocktail party effect. Imagine you‚Äôre at a noisy party, engaged in conversation with someone. All the sudden you hear your name spoken across the room. You brain is constantly filtering through all the auditory information in the room, but you‚Äôre able to pay attention to the person you‚Äôre talking to because your brain is filtering out the other information before it reaches your conscious awareness. But when someone says your name, your brain goes ‚Äúoh that‚Äôs me!‚Äù and your attention is pulled away from the conversation you‚Äôre having because your brain brings that sensory information to your conscious awareness. Does that explanation make sense?
